1️⃣ Client → Backend
Postman sends a POST /upload request with:
Header: Authorization: Bearer <JWT>
Body: form-data → Key: file, Value: chosen image
Express sees this request and passes it through the middleware chain in order:
authMiddleware -> multer upload.single("file") -> uploadFile (controller)
2️⃣ Step inside authMiddleware
JWT is validated
req.user is set → user info is attached
Request moves to next middleware, which is upload.single("file").
3️⃣ Step inside upload.single("file")

Here’s what happens internally in Multer:

a) Parse the request
Multer reads the raw multipart/form-data from the request body
It extracts only the part with key = "file" (because .single("file"))
It parses headers for this part:
Content-Disposition → field name, filename
Content-Type → MIME type

Example parsed info:

{
  fieldname: "file",
  originalname: "myphoto.png",
  encoding: "7bit",
  mimetype: "image/png",
  buffer: <binary data>, // if memory storage
}
b) Check file type (fileFilter)
Multer calls your fileFilter function:
fileFilter(req, file, cb)
file.mimetype.startsWith("image/") ? cb(null, true) : cb(new Error("Only image files allowed"), false)
✅ If file passes → continues
❌ If file fails → skips saving and calls error-handling middleware
c) Check file size (limits)
Multer compares file size with limits.fileSize
If file too large → triggers error → stops processing
d) Store the file (storage)
Multer calls storage object (diskStorage) methods:
destination(req, file, cb) → returns "uploads/"
filename(req, file, cb) → generates filename: Date.now() + "-" + originalname
Then multer writes the file to disk (physical folder)

Example saved file info:

uploads/1774612345678-myphoto.png
e) Attach file info to request
Multer builds req.file object (for .single()):
req.file = {
  fieldname: "file",
  originalname: "myphoto.png",
  encoding: "7bit",
  mimetype: "image/png",
  destination: "uploads/",
  filename: "1774612345678-myphoto.png",
  path: "uploads/1774612345678-myphoto.png",
  size: 102400 // in bytes
}
Important: This is the only thing your controller needs.
Controller doesn’t touch disk storage, filtering, or limits — Multer has already done it.
f) Call next()
After attaching req.file, multer calls next()
Express passes control to your controller uploadFile(req, res)
4️⃣ Controller sees
console.log(req.file);

Output:

{
  fieldname: 'file',
  originalname: 'myphoto.png',
  encoding: '7bit',
  mimetype: 'image/png',
  destination: 'uploads/',
  filename: '1774612345678-myphoto.png',
  path: 'uploads/1774612345678-myphoto.png',
  size: 102400
}
You just read req.file → save the filename, path, and user in MongoDB
Response sent back to client → Done ✅

